data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction is no longer needed. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The signature changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Action<...>`, so manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` code won't compile — and is no longer necessary.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate property names are now uniquified.** Since both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF will auto-append a number (e.g., `Street1`). Pin the names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` column changes from `BillingAddress_City` → `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. Pin it if you need the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, a =>
        {
            a.Property(addr => addr.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Either way, running `dotnet ef migrations add` will generate a rename migration — review it carefully.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Update your implementation:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection,
    DbCommand command,
    DbContext context,
    Guid commandId,
    Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL safe for logging
{
    // Use logCommandText for logs (constants may be redacted)
    // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
}
```

Update all other methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
